     DDDDeeeessssccccrrrriiiippppttttiiiioooonnnn
          _X_l_r_8_s_e_t allows the user to dynamically apply patches to
          SSSSYYYYSSSS0000////SSSSYYYYSSSS(L) and BBBBOOOOOOOOTTTT////SSSSYYYYSSSS(L) that provide improved
          performance on systems equipped with the XLR8er adapter.
          This adapter uses the Hitachi HD64180 or the Zilog Z180
          processor.  Both provide a superset of Z80 instructions.
          These processors also perform many standard Z80 instructions
          in less time than a Z80 running at the same clock speed.

          The patches that _x_l_r_8_s_e_t applies were published in the
          _M_i_s_o_s_y_s _Q_u_a_r_t_e_r_l_y, or are functionally-equivalent, higher-
          performance patches developed by M. A. D. Software.  (The M.
          A. D. Software version of the patches are considerably
          smaller than their predecessors.)

          The benefit is using _x_l_r_8_s_e_t to apply the patches is that
          they do not have to be permanently applied to the
          BBBBOOOOOOOOTTTT////SSSSYYYYSSSS(L) and SSSSYYYYSSSS0000////SSSSYYYYSSSS(L) files on disk.  This allows the
          unused areas in these files to be used for other purposes
          while the system is booting, including booting from devices
          other than the standard floppy disk driver.

          When _x_l_r_8_s_e_t loads patches into memory that require low
          memory space, _x_l_r_8_s_e_t is able to relocate the patches to the
          next available location in low memory, rather than requiring
          the patches to be stored at absolute locations.  _X_l_r_8_s_e_t
          will also refrain from applying the patches if the HD64180
          or Z180 CPU is not present.  This lets you avoid
          reconfiguring the operating system if you need to switch
          over to a plain Z80 CPU for some reason.

          _X_l_r_8_s_e_t accepts several options.  Options are specified by
          single characters, and they may be entered in upper or
          lowercase.  Options are always preceded by a hyphen (a "-").
          If you are specifying multiple options, you can specify the
          options in any of these formats:
                -a -b -c   or   -abc   or   -a -bc   or  -ab -c

          The options are:

          ----qqqq   Causes _x_l_r_8_s_e_t to run silently with no messages being
               displayed if everything works like it should.  Errors
               will be reported.




